Class JSONSerializer

  • java.lang.Object
    • es.ed0.tinyjson.serialization.JSONSerializer

  • public class JSONSerializer
extends java.lang.Object
    Class for serializing plain java objects into JSONObjects, arrays into JSONArrays and viceversa.

      • serializeToJSONObject

        public JSONObject serializeToJSONObject(java.lang.Object obj)
                                 throws JSONException
        Serialize an Object into a JSONObject. The field name will be used as mapping key unless other value was specified using the Key annotation, for the serialization to happen the field must be visible (explicitly be public). Alternatively the class can contain a getter for the field using the standard naming rules: getFieldName() or isFieldName() for boolean types for the field named fieldName. Non-primitive field types like objects will also be serialized into jsons inside the resulting json, same with array types. The annotation Ignore can be used to discard fields during serialization and/or deserialization.
        Parameters:
        obj - Object to serialize
        Returns:
        Serialized json
        Throws:
        JSONException - If an error occurred during serialization. This could be caused by an inaccessible constructor or field.

      • serializeToJSONArray

        public JSONArray serializeToJSONArray(java.lang.Object obj)
                               throws JSONException
        Serialize an array into a JSONArray, note this will only work with array types (i.e int[]) but not with collections. Use collection.toArray() to return a usable array with the collection contents. A JSONArray may be passed for re-serialization.
        Parameters:
        obj - Array to serialize
        Returns:
        Serialized JSONArray
        Throws:
        JSONException - If an error occurred during serialization.

      • serialize

        public java.lang.Object serialize(java.lang.Object obj)
                           throws JSONException
        Serializes any objects into its serialized counter part. Primitive types will return themselves. JSONObjects and JSONArrays will be re-serialized, So any object contained inside them will be serialized into a resulting json containing only jsons and safe to parse. Arrays will be serialized into a JSONArray and other objects will be serialized into JSONObjects. null will return null.
        Parameters:
        obj - Objects to serialize or re-serialize
        Returns:
        serialized object, this can be a primitive type a JSON or null
        Throws:
        JSONException - If the serialization could not be done

      • deserialize

        public <T> T deserialize(java.lang.Object obj,
                         java.lang.Class<T> clazz)
                  throws JSONException
        Deserializes a JSON into an object of the specified type. Like so Pojo pojo = deserialize(json, Pojo.class). This also works with JSONArrays, which can only be deserialized into array types, Pojo[] pojo = deserialize(jsonArray, Pojo[].class).
        A class must contain an empty constructor for it to be deserializable, the field name will be used as key when searching in the json unless other value was specified using the Key annotation. For the deserialization to happen the field must be visible (explicitly be public). Alternatively the class can contain a setter for the field using the standard naming rules: setFieldName() for the field named fieldName. The annotation Ignore can be used to discard fields during serialization and/or deserialization.
        Type Parameters:
        T - Class type
        Parameters:
        obj - Object to deserialize, commonly a json
        clazz - Class type to deserialize to
        Returns:
        Deserialized object of type clazz
        Throws:
        JSONException - If the Object could not be deserialized for any reason.

      • getPrimitiveAs

        public <T> T getPrimitiveAs(java.lang.Object obj,
                            java.lang.Class<T> clazz)
                     throws JSONException
        Casts the primitive object to the given primitive type. Valid primitive objects and types follow: boolean, byte, short, int, float, double, long, char, Boolean, Byte, Short, Integer, Float, Double, Long, Character and String
        Type Parameters:
        T - Class type
        Parameters:
        obj - primitive to cast
        clazz - target primitive type
        Returns:
        the new primitive
        Throws:
        JSONException - if the given object is not a primitive or the casting failed

      • isPrimitive

        public boolean isPrimitive(java.lang.Class<?> clazz)
        Returns whether the given class is a primitive type class. It will output true if the class equals any of the following: boolean, byte, short, int, float, double, long, char, Boolean, Byte, Short, Integer, Float, Double, Long, Character and String.
        Parameters:
        clazz - Class type
        Returns:
        true if the class is a valid primitive, false otherwise
